{"id":"1405.0258","submitter":"Michele Pavanello","authors":"Ruslan Kevorkyants, Henk Eshuis, and Michele Pavanello","title":"FDE-vdW: A van der Waals Inclusive Subsystem Density-Functional Theory","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/1.4890839","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.chem-ph cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a formally exact van der Waals inclusive electronic structure\ntheory, called FDE-vdW, based on the Frozen Density Embedding formulation of\nsubsystem Density-Functional Theory. In subsystem DFT, the energy functional is\ncomposed of subsystem additive and non-additive terms. We show that an\nappropriate definition of the long-range correlation energy is given by the\nvalue of the non-additive correlation functional. This functional is evaluated\nusing the Fluctuation-Dissipation Theorem aided by a formally exact\ndecomposition of the response functions into subsystem contributions. FDE-vdW\nis derived in detail and several approximate schemes are proposed, which lead\nto practical implementations of the method. We show that FDE-vdW is\nCasimir-Polder consistent, i.e. it reduces to the generalized Casimir-Polder\nformula for asymptotic inter-subsystems separations. Pilot calculations of\nbinding energies of 13 weakly bound complexes singled out from the S22 set show\na dramatic improvement upon semilocal subsystem DFT, provided that an\nappropriate exchange functional is employed. The convergence of FDE-vdW with\nbasis set size is discussed, as well as its dependence on the choice of\nassociated density functional approximant.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 1 May 2014 19:16:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-19"}
{"id":"1405.0259","submitter":"David Turton","authors":"Zaq Carson, Shaun Hampton, Samir D. Mathur, David Turton","title":"Effect of the twist operator in the D1D5 CFT","comments":"25 pages, 2 figures, v3: minor clarifications","journal-ref":"JHEP 1408 (2014) 064","doi":"10.1007/JHEP08(2014)064","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The D1D5 CFT has been very useful in the study of black holes. The\ninteraction in this theory involves a twist operator, which links together\ndifferent copies of a free CFT. For the bosonic fields, we examine the action\nof this twist when it links together CFT copies with winding numbers M and N to\nproduce a copy with winding M+N. Starting with the vacuum state generates a\nsqueezed state, which we compute. Starting with an initial excitation on one of\nthe copies gives a linear combination of excitations on the final state, which\nwe also compute. These results generalize earlier computations where these\nquantities were computed for the special case M=N=1. Our results should help in\nunderstanding the thermalization process in the D1D5 CFT, which gives the dual\nof black hole formation in the bulk.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 1 May 2014 19:16:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 5 May 2014 21:12:42 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 30 Oct 2014 15:26:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-10-31"}
